{
  "question_text": "<h3>Merge Intervals</h3><p>Given an array of <code>intervals</code> where <code>intervals[i] = [start_i, end_i]</code>, merge all overlapping intervals, and return an array of the non-overlapping intervals that cover all the intervals in the input.</p>",
  "difficulty": "MEDIUM",
  "marks": 10,
  "input_format": "The first line contains an integer `N`, the number of intervals.\nThe following `N` lines each contain two space-separated integers `start_i` and `end_i`.",
  "output_format": "Output each merged interval on a new line as two space-separated integers `start end`.",
  "constraints": [
    "1 <= intervals.length <= 10^4",
    "intervals[i].length == 2",
    "0 <= start_i <= end_i <= 10^4"
  ],
  "explanation": "To merge overlapping intervals efficiently, we first sort the intervals based on their start coordinate. This crucial step guarantees that any intervals that could potentially overlap will be completely adjacent in our list.\nWe create an empty `merged` array and insert the first interval. Then we iterate through the sorted intervals. For each interval, we compare its start point to the end point of the last interval placed in `merged`. If it's less than or equal (`current_start <= last_merged_end`), it means they overlap! We update the end point of the last interval in `merged` to be the maximum of both end points (`max(last_merged_end, current_end)`). If they don't overlap, we simply append the current interval to `merged`. Sorting takes O(N log N) time, and the linear sweep takes O(N), giving us a highly optimal O(N log N) solution.",
  "answer": "def solve(intervals):\n    intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])\n    merged = []\n    for interval in intervals:\n        if not merged or merged[-1][1] < interval[0]:\n            merged.append(interval)\n        else:\n            merged[-1][1] = max(merged[-1][1], interval[1])\n    return '\\n'.join(f\"{start} {end}\" for start, end in merged)",
  "boilerplate": {
    "python": "import sys\n\ndef solve(intervals):\n    # User logic should be written here\n    return \"\"\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    input_data = sys.stdin.read().split()\n    if not input_data: sys.exit(0)\n    n = int(input_data[0])\n    intervals = []\n    idx = 1\n    for _ in range(n):\n        intervals.append([int(input_data[idx]), int(input_data[idx+1])])\n        idx += 2\n    print(solve(intervals))",
    "cpp": "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <algorithm>\nusing namespace std;\n\nvoid solve(int n, vector<vector<int>>& intervals) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    if (cin >> n) {\n        vector<vector<int>> intervals(n, vector<int>(2));\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {\n            cin >> intervals[i][0] >> intervals[i][1];\n        }\n        solve(n, intervals);\n    }\n    return 0;\n}",
    "java": "import java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void solve(int n, int[][] intervals) {\n        // User logic should be written here\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);\n        if (sc.hasNextInt()) {\n            int n = sc.nextInt();\n            int[][] intervals = new int[n][2];\n            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n                intervals[i][0] = sc.nextInt();\n                intervals[i][1] = sc.nextInt();\n            }\n            solve(n, intervals);\n        }\n        sc.close();\n    }\n}",
    "javascript": "const fs = require('fs');\n\nfunction solve(n, intervals) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n}\n\nconst input = fs.readFileSync(0, 'utf8').trim().split(/\\s+/);\nif (input.length > 0 && input[0] !== '') {\n    const n = parseInt(input[0]);\n    const intervals = [];\n    let idx = 1;\n    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n        intervals.push([parseInt(input[idx]), parseInt(input[idx+1])]);\n        idx += 2;\n    }\n    solve(n, intervals);\n}",
    "c": "#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n\nvoid solve(int n, int** intervals) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    if (scanf(\"%d\", &n) == 1) {\n        int** intervals = (int**)malloc(n * sizeof(int*));\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {\n            intervals[i] = (int*)malloc(2 * sizeof(int));\n            scanf(\"%d %d\", &intervals[i][0], &intervals[i][1]);\n        }\n        solve(n, intervals);\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) free(intervals[i]);\n        free(intervals);\n    }\n    return 0;\n}"
  },
